<subSubSection id="E82CC5AC53E260D7C45C63B0A7D4BBA6" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="7D6BB42A2A9CAD8D9284EB1F05C064E4" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution and habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="09C3C0A3345BF6BEFA7940D4EA61A90D" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName id="C3AC86DFBE58B1FC30C1A41B9D282F7B" class="Liliopsida" family="Haemodoraceae" genus="Pyrrorhiza" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pyrrorhiza neblinae" order="Commelinales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="neblinae">
<emphasis id="15A0DBAE401457436BBEEA57A4CAEB1C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Pyrrorhiza neblinae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is at present only known to occur at the Venezuelan side of the Cerro de la Neblina (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="E7F1ABEAA1C26341716C25DE926DA276" captionStart="Figure 12" captionStartId="F12" captionText="Figure 12. Distribution of Pyrrorhiza neblinae Maguire &amp; Wurdack. Light Green- Subtropical Coniferous Forests; Red - Deserts, Xeric Shrublands, and Tropical Coniferous Forests; Orange - Tropical / Subtropical Grasslands, Savannahs and Shrublands; Maroon - Dry Broadleaf Forests; Green - Moist Broadleaf Forests; Lilac - Montane Grasslands and Shrublands." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.169.57996.figure12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/481938" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">12</figureCitation>
), but most likely also reaches the Brazilian side. It grows in open, acidic, and swampy 
<taxonomicName id="931FC126FC0C2C372D1D79F3124CF13F" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sarraceniaceae" genus="Heliamphora" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Heliamphora" order="Ericales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="0EEB33411AD4CE08C57CF6D4601695F2" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Heliamphora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Benth. (
<taxonomicName id="5E2F6DCC316BEADA1CFC1DD7D060D3EF" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sarraceniaceae" genus="Heliamphora" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Ericales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Sarraceniaceae</taxonomicName>
) and 
<taxonomicName id="AAD721151927B6EA7060C11F9336E416" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Bonnetiaceae" genus="Bonnetia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Bonnetia maguireorum" order="Malpighiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="maguireorum">
<emphasis id="E0570A7C06F3C13071C00000EF628E1C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Bonnetia maguireorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Steyerm. (
<taxonomicName id="8E30E0C644C5B05F66007C01BDC70A7E" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Bonnetiaceae" genus="Bonnetia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Malpighiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Bonnetiaceae</taxonomicName>
) savannahs, with 
<taxonomicName id="EA28CC27D501CA33DBE8B42026ABBB9F" class="Liliopsida" family="Arecaceae" genus="Euterpe" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Euterpe" order="Arecales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="263DD5D052ADBB5C629157CF21291385" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Euterpe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Mart. (
<taxonomicName id="3DC33526253EDF4D2D34FC1DEEC49B79" class="Liliopsida" family="Arecaceae" genus="Euterpe" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Arecales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Arecaceae</taxonomicName>
), along streams, between 1800-2100 m alt. Due to its cormose underground system producing cormlets, 
<taxonomicName id="EF67E5BE68DC0DE79D46D7DEA636D80C" genus="P." lsidName="P. neblinae" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="neblinae">
<emphasis id="D8CD1783B83DE10808F6F34B700F091C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. neblinae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
forms dense clonal clusters. Its pollination syndrome is unknown, but based on the vestigial pair of septal infralocular nectaries, it is most likely a pollen-rewarding, self-compatible species.
</paragraph>
<caption id="FE0423A5A5BEC2E394E3CF8A16E24BC4" doi="10.3897/phytokeys.169.57996.figure12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/481938" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" start="Figure 12" startId="F12">
<paragraph id="1CE61843C5FB43FEFB6A6ABDA4367D02" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
